&nbsp;  
Ascorbic acid, or vitamin C, is not only a key nutrient for human health but also an important addition in beer production, where it is used as an antioxidant to protect against oxidation. Oxidation can negatively affect the taste, aroma, and color of beer, making vitamin C a valuable tool in preserving its qualities.

&nbsp;  
&nbsp;  
# Stages of Adding Vitamin C in Beer Production
![Vitamin C -4.webp](https://udruzenje-kucnih-pivara-srbije.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/Vitamin_C_4_c1b3f0e4a6.webp)
1. **Before Fermentation:** Adding vitamin C to the wort before the start of fermentation can help neutralize the oxygen present in the liquid, laying the foundation for healthy fermentation.
2. **During Dry Hop:** If dry hopping is applied, vitamin C can be added along with hops to reduce the additional oxygen that hops can introduce. This is especially useful when hops are added directly to the fermenter.
3. **Before Bottling/Kegging:** This is a crucial moment to add vitamin C, as this step often encounters the potential risk of oxidation. Vitamin C added just before bottling or kegging can significantly reduce the amount of oxygen dissolved in the beer, thus protecting the beer during storage.

&nbsp;  
&nbsp;  
# Recommended Doses
![Vitamin C -3.webp](https://udruzenje-kucnih-pivara-srbije.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/Vitamin_C_3_cb4df72d46.webp)
The amount of vitamin C added to beer varies depending on specific goals and the timing of addition:
- **Before Fermentation:** Adding about 30-50 mg of vitamin C per liter of wort can be effective in neutralizing oxygen.
- **During Dry Hop:** If vitamin C is added along with hops, the recommended dose remains similar, about 30-50 mg per liter, to ensure protection without affecting the fermentation process.
- **Before Bottling/Kegging:** At this stage, the dose may be slightly higher, up to 100 mg per liter, especially if the beer is packaged under conditions where oxygen control is less stringent.

It is important to note that excessive use of vitamin C can negatively affect the taste of beer, so precise dosing is key. Dissolving vitamin C in a small amount of distilled or boiled and cooled water before adding it to beer can help ensure even distribution.

&nbsp;  
&nbsp;  
# Preparing Vitamin C Before Adding to Beer
![Vitamin C - 2.webp](https://udruzenje-kucnih-pivara-srbije.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/Vitamin_C_2_93221f2485.webp)
Preparing vitamin C (ascorbic acid) before adding it to beer is a crucial step in the brewing process, aiming to maximize its antioxidant benefits. Here are detailed instructions on how to do it properly:
&nbsp;  
**Measuring** Precisely measure the required amount of vitamin C using a digital scale. The amount usually recommended is between 30 to 100 mg per liter of beer, depending on the stage of addition. Accuracy is key to ensure that the recommended dose is not exceeded, as this could negatively impact the taste of the beer.
&nbsp;  
**Dissolving** Ascorbic acid should be dissolved in a small amount of distilled or boiled and cooled water. This helps ensure that vitamin C is evenly distributed throughout the entire batch of beer. The proportion can be, for example, 10 ml of water per 1 gram of vitamin C.
&nbsp;  
**Adding to Beer** The dissolved vitamin C is added directly to the fermenter or the vessel containing the beer, preferably just before bottling or kegging, to reduce the risk of oxidation. If you add vitamin C during dry hopping, ensure that this is done at a time when the risk of introducing additional oxygen is minimized.
&nbsp;  
**Mixing** After adding, gently stir the beer to ensure that vitamin C is fully integrated. This should be done carefully to avoid unnecessary introduction of oxygen into the beer.
&nbsp;  
&nbsp;  
# Conclusion
![Vitamin C - 5.webp](https://udruzenje-kucnih-pivara-srbije.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/Vitamin_C_5_5389b20d18.webp)
Using vitamin C as an antioxidant in beer production offers brewers an effective way to fight oxidation, thus preserving the freshness, taste, and aroma of their products. However, it is important to carefully plan the addition of vitamin C, choose the right moments and doses, to maximize benefits and minimize potential negative effects. With the right approach, vitamin C becomes an indispensable tool in the production of high-quality beer.
&nbsp;  
&nbsp;  
